#Text=Richard Hunne
#Text=Richard
#Text=Hunne
#Text=was an English merchant tailor in the City of London during the early years of the reign of Henry VIII ( 1509-1547 ) .
#Text=After a dispute with his priest over his infant son 's funeral , Hunne sought to use the English common law courts to challenge the church 's authority .
#Text=In response , church officials arrested him for trial in an ecclesiastical court on the capital charge of heresy .
#Text=In December 1514 , while awaiting trial , Hunne was found dead in his cell , and murder by church officials was suspected .
#Text=His death caused widespread anger against the clergy , and months of political and religious turmoil followed .
#Text=Life

#Text=In March 1511 , Hunne refused to pay the standard mortuary fee , the baby 's christening robe , to the rector of St Mary Matfelon in Whitechapel , Thomas Dryffeld , after the funeral of his dead five-week-old son called Stephen .
#Text=The matter was not pursued by the Church until Hunne and a friend challenged the rector of St Michael Cornhill over the title to a tenement in November 1511 .

#Text=Hunne was then sued by the rector of St Mary Matfelon for the mortuary fee and appeared in the ecclesiastical Court of Audience , presided over by Cuthbert Tunstall , chancellor to the Archbishop of Canterbury , in April 1512 .
#Text=The court found in favour of the rector .
#Text=On 27 December 1512 , Hunne attended vespers at the same church and the priest refused to proceed with the service until Hunne left .
#Text=According to the account of Hunne in John Foxe 's Acts and Monuments , [ 1 ] the priest shouted " Hunne , thou art accursed and standest accursed !
